{"types":[{"section":"\n{{fr-noun|m}}\n\n# [[circumflex]] {{gloss|diacritic}}\n#: {{syn|fr|circonflexe|q2=informal or childish|chapeau|chapeau pointu|petit chapeau}}\n#: {{cot|fr|accent aigu|accent grave}}\n\n====Usage notes====\n* The circumflex in Early Modern French indicated [[vowel]] [[length]], which usually resulted from a lost ''s'' or ''e'' by way of [[compensatory lengthening]]. As most of these long vowels (except ''ô'', in some accents ''â'' and ''ê'') have since been shortened, it is now often said that the circumflex is used to represent those lost letters, but this is not its original purpose. Words in which a lost ''s'' did not cause lengthening do not have a circumflex (e.g. {{m|fr|cette}}, {{m|fr|chaque}}, {{m|fr|notre}}).\n\n====Descendants====\n* {{desc|nl|accent circonflexe|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|nb|accent circonflexe|bor=1}}\n\n{{C|fr|Orthography}}\n\n","alt":[],"syn":["circonflexe","chapeau","chapeau pointu","petit chapeau"],"type":"noun","forms":[{"g":"m","n":"s"}],"html":"<p><span class=\"headword-line\"><strong class=\"Latn headword\" lang=\"fr\"><a href=\"/wiki/accent#French\" title=\"accent\">accent</a> <a href=\"/wiki/circonflexe#French\" title=\"circonflexe\">circonflexe</a></strong>&nbsp;<span class=\"gender\"><abbr title=\"masculine gender\">m</abbr></span> (<i>plural</i> <b class=\"Latn form-of lang-fr p-form-of\" lang=\"fr\"><a href=\"/wiki/accents_circonflexes#French\" title=\"accents circonflexes\">accents circonflexes</a></b>)</span>\n</p><ol><li><a href=\"/wiki/circumflex\" title=\"circumflex\">circumflex</a> <span class=\"mention-gloss-paren\">(</span><span class=\"mention-gloss\">diacritic</span><span class=\"mention-gloss-paren\">)</span>\n<dl><dd><span class=\"nyms synonym\"><span class=\"defdate\">Synonyms:</span> <span class=\"Latn\" lang=\"fr\"><a href=\"/wiki/circonflexe#French\" title=\"circonflexe\">circonflexe</a></span>, <span class=\"ib-brac qualifier-brac\">(</span><span class=\"ib-content qualifier-content\">informal o